Romania European country with multicultural music environment which includes active ethnic music scenes Romania also has thriving scenes the fields pop music hip hop heavy metal and rock and roll During the first decade the 21st century some Europop groupsartists such Tom Boxer Morandi Akcent Edward Maya Alexandra Stan Inna and Yarabi achieved success abroadTraditional Romanian folk music remains popular and some folk musicians have come national and even international fame Folk music the oldest form Romanian musical creation characterised great vitality the defining source the cultured musical creation both religious and lay Conservation Romanian folk music has been aided large and enduring audience and numerous performers who helped propagate and further develop the folk sound One them Gheorghe Zamfir famous throughout the world today and helped popularize traditional Romanian folk instrument the panpipes The religious musical creation born under the influence Byzantine music adjusted the intonations the local folk music saw period glory between the 15th and 17th centuries when reputed schools liturgical music developed within Romanian monasteries Russian and Western influences brought about the introduction polyphony religious music the 18th century genre developed series Romanian composers the 19th and 20th centuries Traditional Romanian music reflects confluence sounds similar Central European especially Hungarian well Balkan traditional music Romanian folk music emphasis melody rather than percussion with frequent use the violin for melody and often only the cimbalom for percussion The melody itself and especially the melodic embellishments are reminiscent music from further south the Balkans and distant Turkish influence Banat the violin the most common folk instrument now played alongside imported woodwind instruments other instruments include the taragot today often the saxophone plays the taragot role bands which was imported the 1920s from Hungary Efta Bo